Yes, if your database class is inherited from `SQLiteOpenHelper`, then you need to use its methods for creating and managing the database.

Here's an example of how you can add the parsed data to the database using an `SQLiteOpenHelper`-based database class:

```kotlin
import android.content.ContentValues
import android.content.Context
import android.database.sqlite.SQLiteDatabase
import android.database.sqlite.SQLiteOpenHelper
import org.xml.sax.InputSource
import org.xml.sax.XMLReader
import org.xml.sax.helpers.XMLReaderFactory
import java.io.StringReader

data class Game(val title: String, val developer: String, val year: Int)

class GameDatabase(context: Context) : SQLiteOpenHelper(context, "games.db", null, 1) {

    override fun onCreate(db: SQLiteDatabase) {
        db.execSQL("CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS games(title TEXT, developer TEXT, year INT)")
    }

    override fun onUpgrade(db: SQLiteDatabase, oldVersion: Int, newVersion: Int) {
        db.execSQL("DROP TABLE IF EXISTS games")
        onCreate(db)
    }

    fun addGame(game: Game) {
        val db = writableDatabase
        val values = ContentValues()
        values.put("title", game.title)
        values.put("developer", game.developer)
        values.put("year", game.year)
        db.insert("games", null, values)
        db.close()
    }
}

class GameHandler(private val db: GameDatabase) : org.xml.sax.helpers.DefaultHandler() {

    private var currentElement = ""

    private var title = ""
    private var developer = ""
    private var year = 0

    override fun startElement(uri: String?, localName: String?, qName: String?, attributes: org.xml.sax.Attributes?) {
        currentElement = qName
    }

    override fun characters(ch: CharArray, start: Int, length: Int) {
        val data = String(ch, start, length)
        when (currentElement) {
            "title" -> title += data
            "developer" -> developer += data
            "year" -> year += data.toInt()
        }
    }

    override fun endElement(uri: String?, localName: String?, qName: String?) {
        when (qName) {
            "game" -> {
                val game = Game(title, developer, year)
                db.addGame(game)
                title = ""
                developer = ""
                year = 0
            }
        }
    }
}

fun parseGamesFromXml(xmlString: String, db: GameDatabase) {
    val xr: XMLReader = XMLReaderFactory.createXMLReader()
    xr.contentHandler = GameHandler(db)
    xr.parse(InputSource(StringReader(xmlString)))
}

fun main() {
    val xmlString = "<games><game><title>Super Mario Bros.</title><developer>Nintendo</developer><year>1985</year></game><game><title>The Legend of Zelda</title><developer>Nintendo</developer><year>1986</year></game></games>"
    val context: Context = TODO()
    val db = GameDatabase(context)
    parseGamesFromXml(xmlString, db)
}
```

In this modified example, we define a `GameDatabase` class that inherits from `SQLiteOpenHelper`. In the `onCreate` method, we define the schema of the `games` table. In the `addGame` method, we use the `ContentValues` class to insert a new row into the `games` table.

We also define a `GameHandler` class that inherits from `DefaultHandler` and handles the XML parsing events. Inside the `endElement` method, we create a new `Game` object from the parsed data and call the `addGame` method inside the `GameDatabase` object to add it to the database.

Finally, in the `main` function, we create an instance of `GameDatabase` and call the `parseGamesFromXml` function with the XML string and the `GameDatabase` object to add the parsed data to the database. Note that you need to pass in a valid `Context` object to the `GameDatabase` constructor.

If you need to access the context inside your XML parser to execute the methods of your database class, you could pass the context as an additional parameter to your XML parsing function.

For example, assuming your XML parsing function looks like this:

```kotlin
